#compdef rotel
# =============================================================================
# rotel — Streamfold's "High Performance, Resource
#          Efficient OpenTelemetry Collection" — a Rust-
#          native OpenTelemetry collector daemon designed
#          as a drop-in alternative to the official
#          Go-based opentelemetry-collector (otelcol /
#          otelcol-contrib) with substantially lower
#          memory + CPU footprint, suitable for sidecar +
#          agent deployments where the official Go
#          collector is too heavy.  Built on the
#          opentelemetry-rust crate (the headline CLI
#          library that OPENS Axis 39 on the Rust side;
#          see taxonomy notes below) + tonic for OTLP/gRPC
#          + hyper for OTLP/HTTP + tokio for the async
#          runtime + tower for the middleware retry/timeout
#          machinery.
#          Distinguishing from the official Go otelcol +
#          opentelemetry-collector-contrib (the dominant
#          OTel collector ecosystem), Datadog Agent
#          (DataDog/datadog-agent — Go), Grafana Agent
#          (grafana/agent → grafana/alloy), Vector
#          (vectordotdev/vector — Rust observability
#          router with broader-than-OTel scope), and
#          Cribl Stream (commercial) by:
#            - RUST-NATIVE — written in Rust 2024 edition
#              against rustc 1.91+; no Go GC pauses; no
#              JVM cold-start; built for cgroup-constrained
#              + Lambda + edge sidecar deployments
#            - OPENTELEMETRY-RUST UPSTREAM — uses the
#              official open-telemetry/opentelemetry-rust
#              crates (opentelemetry + opentelemetry_sdk +
#              opentelemetry-proto) directly from git
#              revisions pinned in Cargo.toml.  This is
#              the *upstream* OpenTelemetry implementation
#              for Rust, maintained by the OpenTelemetry
#              project itself (not a third-party fork)
#            - OTLP RECEIVER — accepts OTLP traces/metrics/
#              logs over both gRPC (via tonic) and HTTP
#              (via hyper).  Default OTLP gRPC port 4317,
#              OTLP HTTP port 4318.  TLS support via
#              hyper-rustls + rustls v0.23
#            - PROCESSORS via DYNAMIC LIBRARIES — unique
#              feature: load Rust-compiled .so/.dylib
#              processor plugins at runtime via `--rust-
#              trace-processor`, `--rust-logs-processor`,
#              `--rust-metrics-processor` (sync) +
#              `--async-rust-trace-processor` /
#              `--async-rust-logs-processor` / `--async-
#              rust-metrics-processor` (async).  This
#              gives the dynamic-loading flexibility of
#              the Go collector's processor pipeline
#              without paying the runtime cost of Go's
#              plugin system
#            - MULTI-EXPORTER FAN-OUT — `--exporters
#              name:type,...` configures multiple named
#              exporters; `--exporters-traces` / `--
#              exporters-metrics` / `--exporters-logs`
#              route different signal types to different
#              destinations independently
#            - EXPORTER TYPES — otlp / blackhole /
#              datadog / clickhouse / awsxray / awsemf /
#              kafka (feature `rdkafka`) / file (feature
#              `file_exporter`).  Datadog exporter uses
#              the DD intake API directly; ClickHouse
#              exporter writes to a ClickHouse server for
#              SQL-queryable observability; AWS X-Ray +
#              EMF exporters send to native AWS observability
#              backends without an intermediate hop
#            - RECEIVER TYPES — otlp / kafka (feature
#              `rdkafka`) / fluent (feature
#              `fluent_receiver`) / file (feature
#              `file_receiver`) / kmsg (Linux-only,
#              feature `kmsg_receiver`).  Fluent receiver
#              ingests fluentd/fluent-bit forward protocol;
#              kmsg receiver reads Linux kernel logs
#              directly
#            - BATCH SHAPING — `--batch-max-size` /
#              `--batch-timeout` plus per-signal overrides
#              `--traces-batch-max-size`, `--metrics-
#              batch-max-size`, `--logs-batch-max-size`
#              for fine-grained backpressure control
#            - RETRY MIDDLEWARE — tower::retry-based
#              exporter retry with configurable max-
#              retries + initial backoff + max backoff +
#              backoff multiplier via the
#              `GlobalExporterRetryArgs` flattened-args
#              group
#            - DAEMONIZE — `--daemon` forks to background
#              + writes `--pid-file` + `--log-file`;
#              integrates with systemd / launchd /
#              supervisord / sysvinit
#            - DEBUG-LOG PIPELINE INSPECTION — `--debug-
#              log traces|metrics|logs` enables in-process
#              logging of every span/metric/log point
#              flowing through the pipeline, with
#              `--debug-log-verbosity basic|detailed|
#              verbose` controlling depth.  Critical for
#              configuration debugging in production
#            - INTERNAL TELEMETRY — `--enable-internal-
#              telemetry` causes rotel itself to emit its
#              own OTel metrics about ingest rate /
#              export latency / queue depth / retry
#              counts, suitable for ingestion back into
#              the same pipeline
#            - PROMETHEUS METRICS ENDPOINT — feature
#              `prometheus` enables `--prometheus-endpoint
#              host:port` which scrapes rotel's internal
#              metrics in Prometheus exposition format
#              (alternative to internal-telemetry-via-OTel)
#            - PROFILING — feature `pprof` adds `--pprof-
#              flame-graph` / `--pprof-call-graph` for
#              CPU profile capture against the running
#              agent
#            - 367+ STARS ON rotel-dev/rotel — backed by
#              Streamfold (streamfold.com) as the
#              commercial entity; the rotel project itself
#              is Apache 2.0
#          Used by: edge-deployment teams replacing
#          Go-based otelcol with a smaller-footprint agent,
#          AWS Lambda extension developers needing OTel
#          collection inside a 128 MB execution environment,
#          Kubernetes operators running per-pod OTel
#          sidecars without dedicating 100+ MB to the
#          collector, and IoT/embedded contexts where the
#          Go collector cannot fit.
#
# Author:  Streamfold (streamfold.com) — the commercial
#          entity backing rotel.  Maintained under the
#          rotel-dev GitHub organization at
#          https://rotel.dev/.
# Source:  https://github.com/rotel-dev/rotel
#          https://github.com/rotel-dev/rotel/blob/main/src/bin/rotel/main.rs
#          https://github.com/rotel-dev/rotel/blob/main/src/init/args.rs
#          https://github.com/rotel-dev/rotel/blob/main/src/init/batch.rs
#          https://github.com/rotel-dev/rotel/blob/main/src/init/otlp_exporter.rs
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `rotel start --help`
#          shows all the options (extensive, ~80 flags);
#          `rotel version` prints version info.
# Library: opentelemetry + opentelemetry_sdk +
#          opentelemetry-proto (open-telemetry/
#          opentelemetry-rust, pinned to git revision
#          0948c61 in Cargo.toml for ARM-32 AtomicU64
#          fix).  This is the headline dependency for
#          this completion's axis-opening role; see
#          taxonomy notes below.  Also clap 4.5 (Axis 1
#          argparse), tokio 1.43 (async runtime), tonic
#          0.14 (gRPC), hyper 1 + hyper-util + hyper-
#          rustls + rustls 0.23 (HTTP/TLS), prost 0.14
#          (Protobuf), tracing + tracing-subscriber +
#          tracing-bunyan-formatter + tracing-log
#          (Axis 9 logging — bunyan-formatter for JSON
#          structured output), flume 0.11 (async channel),
#          tower 0.5 + tower-http 0.6 (middleware retry/
#          timeout/compression), flate2 (compression with
#          zlib-ng feature for faster zlib), daemonize
#          (background process), humantime (duration
#          parsing for `--batch-timeout 200ms`), pprof
#          0.14 (CPU profiling with flamegraph), rand,
#          bytes, http, futures, url.
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  367+ stars on rotel-dev/rotel; active
#          development (latest commit May 28, 2026).
